McCay's original artwork has been poorly preserved.{{sfn|Heer|2006}} McCay insisted on having his originals returned to him, and a large collection that survived him was destroyed in a fire in the late 1930s. His wife was unsure how to handle the surviving pieces, so his son took on the responsibility and moved the collection to his own house.{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|p=253}} The family sold off some of the artwork when they were in need of cash. Responsibility for it passed to Mendelsohn, then later to daughter Marion. By the early twenty-first century, most of McCay's surviving artwork remained in family hands.{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|pp=253–254}}

McCay destroyed many of his original cans of film to create more storage space. Of what film he kept, much has not survived, as it was photographed on 35mm [[硝化纤维|nitrate film]], which decomposes and is highly flammable. Mendelsohn's son and a friend, both young animators, discovered the film in Mendelsohn's possession in 1947 and rescued what they could. In some cases, such as ''The Centaurs'', only fragments could be saved. A {{tsl|en|negative (photography)||negative}} and incomplete positive was discovered of ''Performing Animals'', a film of animals playing instruments that may have been intended for McCay's vaudeville act; it was deemed unsalvageable and destroyed.{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|p=254}}

In 1966, cartoonist {{tsl|en|Woody Gelman||Woody Gelman}} discovered the original artwork for many ''Little Nemo'' strips at a cartoon studio where McCay's son Robert had worked. Many of the recovered originals were displayed at the [[大都會藝術博物館|Metropolitan Museum of Art]] under the direction of curator {{tsl|en|A. Hyatt Mayor||A. Hyatt Mayor}}. In 1973, Gelman published a collection of ''Little Nemo'' strips in Italy.{{sfn|Jamieson|2010|p=126}} His collection of McCay originals is preserved at the {{tsl|en|Billy Ireland Cartoon Library & Museum||Billy Ireland Cartoon Library & Museum}} at [[俄亥俄州立大学|Ohio State University]].{{sfn|Spencer|2005}}

[[File:Walt_disney_portrait.jpg|upright=0.8]] acknowledged his debt to McCay's example.]]

McCay's work, grounded solidly in his understanding of realistic perspective, presaged the techniques featured in [[华特迪士尼公司|Walt Disney]]'s feature films.{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|p=31}} Disney paid tribute to McCay in 1955 on an episode of ''{{tsl|en|Walt Disney anthology television series||Disneyland}}''. The episode, "The Story of Animated Drawing", gave a history of animation, and dramatized McCay's vaudeville act with ''Gertie''. Robert was invited to the Disney studios as a consultant on the episode, where Disney told him, "Bob, all this should be your father's".{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|p=255}}

Animator and McCay biographer John Canemaker produced a film in 1974 called ''Remembering Winsor McCay'', narrated by McCay's animation assistant John Fitzsimmons. Canemaker helped coordinate the first retrospective of McCay's films at the third International Animation Film Festival in 1975 in New York, which led to a film show at the [[惠特尼美国艺术博物馆|Whitney Museum of American Art]] in winter 1975–76.{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|p=255}} Canemaker also wrote a biography in 1987 called ''Winsor McCay: His Life and Art''. In 2005, a revised and expanded version of the biography was released, which comics scholar Jeet Heer called "far and away the most scholarly and intelligent biography ever written about an American cartoonist".{{sfn|Heer|2006}} Animation scholar Paul Wells stated, "McCay's influence on the history of animation cannot be understated".{{sfn|Wells|2006|p=89}} Film critic {{tsl|en|Richard Eder||Richard Eder}} lamented that as an animation pioneer McCay was not able to reach the potential suggested by his work. Eder compared McCay to the {{tsl|en|Italian primitives||Italian primitives}} of the early Renaissance, highly skilled "in the limited techniques they could command".{{sfn|Canemaker|2005|p=199}} Heer wrote that McCay's strength was in his visuals, but that his writing and characters were weak.{{sfn|Heer|2006}}

[[File:Little_Nemo_in_Slumberland_mural_downtown_Cincinnati,_OH_Oct_2016.jpg|thumb]]
Italian filmmaker [[费德里柯·费里尼|Federico Fellini]] read ''Little Nemo'' in the children's magazine ''{{tsl|en|Corriere dei Piccoli||Il corriere dei piccoli}}'', and the strip was a "powerful influence" on the filmmaker, according to Fellini biographer {{tsl|en|Peter Bondanella||Peter Bondanella}}.{{sfn|Bondanella|2002|p=10}} Comics historian {{tsl|en|R. C. Harvey||R. C. Harvey}} has called McCay "the first original genius of the comic strip medium" and in animation. Harvey said that McCay's contemporaries lacked the skill to continue with his innovations, so that they were left for future generations to rediscover and build upon.{{sfn|Harvey|1994|p=21}}

McCay's work has inspired cartoonists from [[卡尔·巴克斯|Carl Barks]]{{sfn|Ault|Andrae|Gong|2003|p=91}} to {{tsl|en|Art Spiegelman||Art Spiegelman}}.{{sfn|Jacobowitz|2007|p=164}} [[罗伯特·克朗姆|Robert Crumb]] called McCay a "genius" and one of his favorite cartoonists. {{tsl|en|Art Spiegelman||Art Spiegelman}}'s 1974 "Real Dream" strip was partially inspired by ''Rarebit Fiend'',{{sfn|Young|2000}} and his ''{{tsl|en|In the Shadow of No Towers||In the Shadow of No Towers}}'' in 2004 appropriated some of McCay's imagery, and included a page of ''Little Nemo'' in its appendix.{{sfn|Heer|2006}} [[莫里斯·桑達克|Maurice Sendak]]'s children's book ''{{tsl|en|In the Night Kitchen||In the Night Kitchen}}'' (1970) was an homage to McCay's work,{{sfn|Nel|2005|p=204}} as was {{tsl|en|Rick Veitch||Rick Veitch}}' comic book series ''Roarin' Rick's Rarebit Fiends'' (1994–96).{{sfn|Markstein|2007}} {{tsl|en|Kim Deitch||Kim Deitch}} and Simon Deitch's graphic novel ''{{tsl|en|The Boulevard of Broken Dreams (comics)||The Boulevard of Broken Dreams}}'' revolved around a character named Winsor Newton,{{efn|A pun on {{tsl|en|Winsor & Newton||Winsor & Newton}}, whose ink brushes are popular with cartoonists.}} based on an aged McCay.{{sfn|Gardner|2012|p=158}} Cartoonist {{tsl|en|Berke Breathed||Berke Breathed}} lamented that the conditions of newspaper cartooning had devolved to such a degree since McCay's time that, had he worked later in the century, he would not have been allotted space sufficient for his expansive full-page fantasies.{{sfn|Harvey|1994|p=28}}

[[File:A_French_Nurse's_Dream_(crop).jpg|thumb]]'s ''[[夢的解析|The Interpretation of Dreams]]'' (1914) contained a comic strip by Nándor Honti that resembled McCay's work.]]

As [[西格蒙德·弗洛伊德|Sigmund Freud]]'s ''[[夢的解析|The Interpretation of Dreams]]'' first appeared in print in 1899, McCay's major dream strips work have invited speculation of a Freudian influence. "A French Nurse's Dream", a comic strip by the Hungarian artist Nándor Honti that appeared in Freud's book edition in 1914, strongly resembles the work of McCay in its theme,{{sfn|Roeder|2014|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=I_gaBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA205 205]}} pacing, Art Nouveau style, and closing panel of the dreamer awakening in bed. However, the English translation of Freud's book was not published until 1913.{{sfn|Shannon|2010|pp=191–193}}

The {{tsl|en|Winsor McCay Award||Winsor McCay Award}} was established in 1972 to recognize individuals for lifetime or career contributions in animation, and is presented as part of the [[安妮獎|Annie Award]]s.{{sfn|Dixon|2008}} The {{tsl|en|Hammer Museum||Hammer Museum}} in Los Angeles devoted a room to McCay's work as part of the ''Masters of American Comics'' exhibit in 2005.{{sfn|Heer|2006}} German publisher [[塔森出版社|Taschen]] published a complete, boxed, full-size edition of ''Little Nemo'' in two volumes in 2014 entitled ''The Complete Little Nemo''.{{sfn|Taube|2014}}

The American astronomer {{tsl|en|Roy A. Tucker||Roy A. Tucker}} named the asteroid [[小行星列表/113001-114000|113461]] after McCay in 2002.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://minorplanetcenter.net/db_search/show_object?object_id=113461 |title=IAU Minor Planet Center |publisher=IAU Minor Planet Center |access-date=September 15, 2018 }}</ref>

